01:29:28,238 --> 01:29:30,115
Just the opposite.

1021
01:29:33,410 --> 01:29:35,662
It was never like that with him.

1022
01:29:43,253 --> 01:29:45,797
I never thought it could be like that.

1023
01:29:50,343 --> 01:29:51,928
What about you?

1024
01:29:52,679 --> 01:29:55,223
The way I am...

1025
01:29:56,057 --> 01:29:59,561
doesn’t mean I can’t make love to a woman.

1026
01:29:59,811 --> 01:30:01,605
It’s different.

1027
01:30:03,607 --> 01:30:05,358
It was very nice...

1028
01:30:05,692 --> 01:30:07,777
but it doesn’t change anything.

1029
01:30:30,634 --> 01:30:32,802
Meeting you, getting to know you...

1030
01:30:33,470 --> 01:30:36,014
talking with you,
spending the whole day with you -

1031
01:30:36,640 --> 01:30:38,642
today of all days -

1032
01:30:39,225 --> 01:30:42,103
has been very important for me.

1033
01:30:58,161 --> 01:31:01,122
I’ll look across at
your window every day...

1034
01:31:02,666 --> 01:31:06,169
the way I did this morning
when I went back home.

1035
01:31:07,879 --> 01:31:09,881
I kept watching you.

1036
01:31:10,090 --> 01:31:12,592
I couldn’t get anything done.

1037
01:31:15,720 --> 01:31:18,848
And next Saturday,
when everyone goes off to the rally...

1038
01:31:21,935 --> 01:31:24,354
it’ll be enough just to see you...

1039
01:31:25,689 --> 01:31:27,732
and hear your voice.

1040
01:31:32,028 --> 01:31:34,072
Good evening.

1041
01:31:34,614 --> 01:31:36,491
How was the parade?

1042
01:31:36,616 --> 01:31:40,578
Wonderful, huh?
I heard it all on the radio.

1043
01:31:46,668 --> 01:31:48,628
They’re coming back.

1044
01:31:48,920 --> 01:31:50,505
I have to go.

1045
01:33:40,406 --> 01:33:43,243
Good evening, sir, ma’am.

1046
01:33:43,535 --> 01:33:46,746
I listened to the whole thing on the radio.

1047
01:33:47,205 --> 01:33:49,332
Did you have a good time?

1048
01:33:49,457 --> 01:33:52,669
What’s Hitler like?
- He’s so handsome!

1049
01:33:54,128 --> 01:33:58,716
I heard it all on the radio.
I enjoyed every minute.

1050
01:33:58,925 --> 01:34:01,511
Was the parade nice?
- Great.

1051
01:34:01,803 --> 01:34:05,098
A historic day for Italy! -1 agree.

1052
01:34:10,019 --> 01:34:12,689
- Did you see that fat general?
- That was Goering.

1053
01:34:12,814 --> 01:34:16,025
- Wasn’t it Hess?
- He’s the crazy-looking one.

1054
01:34:16,192 --> 01:34:18,653
The entire top brass of
our great sister nation.

1055
01:34:18,778 --> 01:34:20,280
My feet hurt.

1056
01:34:33,084 --> 01:34:35,712
- Fulvio, did you get tired?
- No.

1057
01:35:01,821 --> 01:35:04,324
We were all shouting, “Duce! Duce! Duce!”

1058
01:35:04,449 --> 01:35:06,576
And he was lapping it up.

1059
01:35:06,743 --> 01:35:09,662
But then he gestured
toward Hitler as if to say,

1060
01:35:09,787 --> 01:35:13,249
“Don’t forget our guest,” and
everyone clapped even louder.

1061
01:35:13,416 --> 01:35:18,004
- I didn’t see that.
- You were too far away. I saw it all.

1062
01:35:18,129 --> 01:35:21,382
Antonietta, you really missed something.

1063
01:35:22,091 --> 01:35:25,261
Hey, am I supposed to eat
my minestrone with a fork?

1064
01:35:25,428 --> 01:35:27,430
What’s the matter
with you tonight?

1065
01:35:29,098 --> 01:35:31,100
A fateful day.

1066
01:35:31,768 --> 01:35:33,686
Unforgettable.

1067
01:35:34,145 --> 01:35:36,481
And you all had the privilege

1068
01:35:36,606 --> 01:35:38,691
of witnessing it in person.

1069
01:35:38,816 --> 01:35:43,196
In 20 or 30 years’ time you
can tell your children...

1070
01:35:44,113 --> 01:35:46,407
“I was the re that day”

1071
01:35:48,034 --> 01:35:50,620
They gave me one bread roll all day.

1072
01:35:53,247 --> 01:35:55,792
- What’s all this?
- The pom-pom.

1073
01:35:55,959 --> 01:35:58,461
Mom, pass the mortadella.

1074
01:36:00,338 --> 01:36:04,133
A cold dinner.
Didn’t do a thing all day, did you?

1075
01:36:04,300 --> 01:36:06,260
Wasn’t it a national holiday?

1076
01:36:06,386 --> 01:36:09,514
And you stayed home in bed.

1077
01:36:12,141 --> 01:36:15,228
We have more tanks than the rest of Europe.

1078
01:36:15,353 --> 01:36:16,980
Even more than America, Dad?

1079
01:36:17,146 --> 01:36:19,732
Sure. All they can do is make movies.

1080
01:36:19,857 --> 01:36:23,653
They’re still fighting the
Indians with bows and arrows.

1081
01:36:24,654 --> 01:36:26,990
I think the air force is the most exciting.

1082
01:36:27,156 --> 01:36:29,659
- No, the navy.
- Shows what you know.

1083
01:36:29,784 --> 01:36:32,328
Too bad we didn’t see any ships.

1084
01:36:32,495 --> 01:36:35,915
Right. Imagine a battleship parading past!

1085
01:36:36,040 --> 01:36:38,835
- Will you cut it out?
- Hands off!

1086
01:36:38,960 --> 01:36:41,754
You’ll have lots of pictures
for your album, Mom.

1087
01:36:44,007 --> 01:36:47,802
There’ll be lots of pictures
to clip in tomorrow’s paper.

1088
01:36:50,263 --> 01:36:52,348
I’m hoarse from all the singing.

1089
01:36:52,473 --> 01:36:54,434
You see the German band on horseback?

1090
01:36:54,559 --> 01:36:56,352
They were fantastic!

1091
01:36:56,519 --> 01:36:58,730
I don’t know how they do it.

1092
01:36:58,855 --> 01:37:02,525
It’s the Fuhrer’s personal band.
They’re with him everywhere.

1093
01:37:02,650 --> 01:37:04,193
Even at home.

1094
01:37:04,360 --> 01:37:06,904
Mom, Littorio’s eating with his left hand.

1095
01:37:07,030 --> 01:37:11,200
How come the Germans do the
goose step better than us?

1096
01:37:11,367 --> 01:37:13,244
Because it’s hard!

1097
01:37:13,369 --> 01:37:15,872
Come on.
We’re pretty impressive too.

1098
01:37:16,039 --> 01:37:18,708
Did you see the Alpine Corps?
- Sure did.

1099
01:37:18,875 --> 01:37:21,711
But the German uniforms
are much more elegant.

1100
01:37:21,919 --> 01:37:25,882
You gotta admit: We know
how to pick our allies, huh?

1101
01:37:26,007 --> 01:37:27,800
If there’s another war,

1102
01:37:27,925 --> 01:37:30,678
we’ll kick all their asses!

1103
01:38:03,461 --> 01:38:07,173
Antonie, a day like today
calls for a celebration,

1104
01:38:07,298 --> 01:38:09,967
and if we have a seventh,
we’ll call him Adolf.

1105
01:38:10,093 --> 01:38:12,428
No, not tonight.

1106
01:38:12,762 --> 01:38:14,931
Just hurry up and come to bed.

1107
01:38:19,102 --> 01:38:20,895
We’ll discuss it then.

1108
01:39:19,495 --> 01:39:23,082
“That first Monday of April 1625,

1109
01:39:23,207 --> 01:39:24,876
the town of Meung,

1110
01:39:25,001 --> 01:39:27,753
birthplace of the author
of the Romance of the Rose,

1111
01:39:27,879 --> 01:39:29,797
was in complete chaos,

1112
01:39:29,922 --> 01:39:33,676
as if the Huguenots aimed to
make of it a second La Rochelle.”

1113
01:41:01,973 --> 01:41:05,434
- I’m just about ready.
- Take your time.

1114
01:41:05,559 --> 01:41:08,271
- When does the boat leave?
- In three hours.

1115
01:41:36,632 --> 01:41:40,636
“Imagine a Don Quixote aged
18, with a long face

1116
01:41:53,566 --> 01:41:57,194
“...a long face with high
cheekbones, a sign of craftiness

1117
01:42:32,980 --> 01:42:36,233
“...all the more painful
to young D’Artagnan...”

